00:00:43.130 --> 00:00:46.210
We're talking about applications
of the spontaneous light force.

00:00:46.210 --> 00:00:51.230
We have used optical
block recreations and such

00:00:51.230 --> 00:00:55.480
to learn about the spontaneous
force, the stimulated force,

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:57.100
in general.

00:00:57.100 --> 00:01:01.850
And this is our expression for
the spontaneous light force.

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:05.260
It's pretty much, the
momentum of photons

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:09.100
is transferred to the atom
times to scattering rate.

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:14.040
And what we started last class,
and we want to finish today,

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:20.790
is we want to discuss
applications of this force

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:25.320
to three situations which are
of experimental importance.

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:28.800
One can actually say that
slow beams, more or less,

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:32.690
in the magneto-optical trap
are the key techniques which

00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:35.460
triggered a revolution
in atomic physics.

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.680
This is really the
enabling technology

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:42.700
into ultracold atom science.

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:49.110
So I discussed with you, in
the last class, molasses.

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:56.040
And we discussed
what happens when

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:58.600
we have two
counterpropagating beams.

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:03.460
Maybe the key figure to
remember is this one.

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:05.890
When we have to
counterpropagating beams,

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:08.860
by just adding up the
spontaneous light force

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:14.820
of the two beams, we get the red
curve, force versus velocity.

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:18.130
And the expert eye immediately
sees there is a linear slope.

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:20.190
And that's a viscous force.

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:24.782
This is the viscosity of
light interacting with atoms.

00:02:24.782 --> 00:02:27.990
Of course, you'd better
pick the detuning correctly.

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:30.040
If you use the wrong
detuning, everything

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:31.630
is flipped upside down.

00:02:31.630 --> 00:02:34.915
And instead of a damping force,
you have an anti-damping force.

00:02:39.430 --> 00:02:42.470
We then discussed
the cooling limit.

00:02:42.470 --> 00:02:51.335
Any cooling limit is the balance
between heating and cooling.

00:02:51.335 --> 00:02:54.810
And by just setting the heating
rate equal to the cooling rate,

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:56.600
this describes a steady state.

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:58.650
We found the famous
Doppler limit.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:01.540
OK.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.110
So that's where I
want to continue.

00:03:03.110 --> 00:03:06.710
But do you have any
questions about molasses,

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:11.320
the Doppler limit, and what we
discussed in the last class?

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:20.490
Well, I know we had discussions
about to take two beams which

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:24.390
form a standing wave, and
take it apart, and calculate

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:26.250
the force for each beam.

00:03:26.250 --> 00:03:28.810
Well, sorry, this is
what molasses is about.

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:30.590
Molasses is about two beams.

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:34.290
And if you want to treat
two interfering laser

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:38.100
beams in the full
generality, there

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:39.560
are a lot of other effects.

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:41.310
Some of them, we
will be uncovering

00:03:41.310 --> 00:03:43.620
in the next few lectures.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:47.400
But I'm happy now, when
I discuss beam slowing,

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:51.870
to give you when there
is only one single laser

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:55.070
beam decelerating atoms.

00:03:55.070 --> 00:03:57.590
That is the only
situation I know

00:03:57.590 --> 00:04:01.080
about where you have an
exact analytic solution.

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:03.525
So I want to present
it to you know.

00:04:03.525 --> 00:04:07.020
Actually, for a number of years,
I presented the exact solution

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:10.720
with one laser beam before
I presented molasses,

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:13.260
where I have to
make approximations.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:17.420
But I always felt that beam
slowing is more complicated,

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:19.829
because you have to go
to a decelerating frame

00:04:19.829 --> 00:04:21.690
and have to add
fictitious forces.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:23.720
So some of the
intuition is lost.

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:27.250
So that's why I first
presented you with molasses,

00:04:27.250 --> 00:04:30.540
with two beams, for which I
need to make approximations.

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:33.720
Because the interference
pattern between two laser beams

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:36.380
has richness and complexity.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:39.590
But now I discuss
beam slowing with you.

00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:44.830
So this curve here
could be the result

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:48.110
of the very early beginnings
of laser cooling in

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:51.400
the late '70s, early '80s.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:56.050
And this is when people had an
atomic beam with a Boltzmann

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:59.960
distribution, and they had one
laser been counterpropagating.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:02.390
But the laser beam
had a fixed frequency.

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:04.410
And what is this
laser beam doing?

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:07.450
Well, it resonantly
interacts with the atoms

00:05:07.450 --> 00:05:09.920
which just have the
correct Doppler shift

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:11.310
to be in resonance.

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:15.770
Those atoms are pushed--
scattered photons-- are pushed

00:05:15.770 --> 00:05:19.110
to lower frequencies--
to lower velocities.

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:21.040
But they are pushed
out of resonance.

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:24.610
And eventually, the slowing
becomes slower and slower.

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.810
And eventually, things come,
almost, to a standstill.

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:31.500
So a laser beam which
has a fixed frequency

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:34.790
would modify the
velocity distribution

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:39.360
of an atomic beam in that way.

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:40.980
People called it,
already, cooling.

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:42.950
And I think some
pioneers in Russia

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:47.760
who did those experiments were
disappointed that they were not

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.120
honored with a Nobel
Prize in laser cooling.

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:51.260
This was the first cooling.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:54.830
Because this distribution
here is considerably narrower

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:55.580
than here.

00:05:55.580 --> 00:05:58.605
And temperature is nothing
else than a measure

00:05:58.605 --> 00:06:02.640
of the reach of the
velocity distribution.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:06.060
But one can say that
those experiments did not

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:07.830
trigger a revolution
in atomic physics.

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:11.460
The revolution came when
people eventually figured out

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:17.800
how they can narrow down this
peak from maybe a hundred

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:22.410
or tens of kelvins down
to a million microkelvin.

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:24.790
So it's clear what is needed.

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:27.380
If you want to do
more slowing, you

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:30.150
have to make sure
that you are talking

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:32.400
to the other velocities,
and that you eventually

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:36.420
sweep many velocities into one
peak-- clear out the velocity

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:38.670
distribution, collect
all the atoms,

00:06:38.670 --> 00:06:41.850
and put them at a
monochromatic velocity.

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:47.200
So for that, you can say, well,
if you use a comb of frequency,

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.550
or a broad spectrum
of frequencies,

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:52.430
you could clean
out a larger area.

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:54.140
And, indeed, there
are techniques

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:59.640
like this-- white light slowing
or diffuse light slowing.

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:02.220
But since those
techniques are not

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:07.430
anymore of practical importance,
I don't want to discuss them.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:12.110
Let me talk about the
simplest technique-- at least,

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:15.950
conceptionally-- which
is chirped slowing.

00:07:15.950 --> 00:07:18.390
And this works like follows.

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:20.620
You start with a laser
beam which is initially

00:07:20.620 --> 00:07:22.750
in resonance with
the velocity group.

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:27.710
And as the atoms slow down,
you change the detuning

00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:30.810
of the laser that the
laser stays in resonance

00:07:30.810 --> 00:07:33.670
with the atoms.

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:36.870
So it is a pulsed
technique where

00:07:36.870 --> 00:07:39.180
you have a continuous
atomic beam.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:42.570
You start with a laser and
say, now I start slowing.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:46.055
And the laser is
following a group of atoms

00:07:46.055 --> 00:07:47.305
as they are decelerated.

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:53.940
So you can say it is like the
atoms are riding the surf.

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:56.140
The laser is always
following the atoms

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:58.540
as they change their velocity.

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:01.020
And what is, of course,
necessary for that to happen

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:03.590
is that the chirp and the
deceleration of the atoms

00:08:03.590 --> 00:08:04.895
are synchronized.

00:08:04.895 --> 00:08:06.960
You will see that
in a moment, when

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:11.170
I put this idea into equations.

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:14.440
There is another technique
which is used in many labs--

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:17.350
actually, in all my labs
and Martin Zwierlein's lab.

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:19.000
It's called Zeeman slowing.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.690
And this is discussed
in your homework.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:25.320
It is a CW version
of chirped slowing.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.040
And a lot of you
know what I mean.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:33.080
The physics which goes on
there is almost identical.

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:35.390
But for conceptional
reasons, it's

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:38.200
easier not to use
magnetic fields and such.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:39.710
Let's just keep it simple.

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:44.720
Let's have one laser beam
talking to a two-level atom.

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:49.660
And the only other ingredient
is the Doppler shift.

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:53.320
Any questions about--
so I've surveyed,

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:54.820
for you, beam slowing.

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:59.160
And now I want to give
you the exact description

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.160
for one typical example
of a slowing technique.

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:04.734
And a lot of the results
we find in chirped slowing

00:09:04.734 --> 00:09:06.150
apply to other
slowing techniques.

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:10.740
OK.

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.870
I know I've taught
it several times.

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:19.770
And there is the
conceptional point

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:23.630
that you can only describe
chirped slowing well

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:26.920
when you go to the decelerating
frame of the atoms.

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:30.600
You want to describe it in
the frame of the atoms which

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:33.260
are continuously
being decelerated.

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:37.970
So the way I can introduce
it is the following.

00:09:37.970 --> 00:09:42.800
I take the maximum-- I take
the spontaneous light force.

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:44.240
This is exactly
the expression we

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:47.360
have discussed several times.

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:53.930
And now I'm saying
we decide that we

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:57.700
want to decelerate atoms
with a deceleration, a, which

00:09:57.700 --> 00:10:00.240
is negative, because
we slow them down.

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:03.810
Of course, if you pick a too
large that it would require

00:10:03.810 --> 00:10:05.850
more than the maximum
spontaneous light force,

00:10:05.850 --> 00:10:07.350
you will not find a solution.

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:12.450
But let's simply assume we
want to decelerate atoms

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:15.090
with a deceleration a.

00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:17.810
Well, what happens is
this deceleration, a,

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:19.640
requires a certain force.

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:23.280
If the intensity of the laser
would provide more force

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:26.630
on resonance then it's
not going to work.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:29.790
Because we want to decelerate
the atoms at this deceleration.

00:10:29.790 --> 00:10:33.820
So therefore, the atoms,
if they are decelerated,

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:38.420
have to be at a detuning,
delta prime, in such a way

00:10:38.420 --> 00:10:42.680
that the spontaneous
light force is exactly

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:45.860
providing the
acceleration we decided

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:48.700
we want to have for our atoms.

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:53.580
In other words, this detuning--
in the frame of the atom,

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:58.140
the atoms are on resonance
when the light force is exactly

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:01.330
providing the force to give
you the acceleration a.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:05.520
But if you have more laser
power than absolutely necessary,

00:11:05.520 --> 00:11:07.770
in the frame of the
atoms, the atoms

00:11:07.770 --> 00:11:12.670
have to be detuned in
such a way that the force,

00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:15.260
with the detuning,
is exactly providing

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.930
the acceleration we want.

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:22.650
So that's the easiest
way to explain it.

00:11:22.650 --> 00:11:25.110
We have to set the stage.

00:11:25.110 --> 00:11:29.310
We have to introduce
this nominal detuning.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:29.810
OK.

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:37.150
So you can say that this
detuning is just a definition.

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:41.850
And now we want to describe
the slowing process.

00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:47.210
So we have said we want
to start with atoms

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:50.290
at an initial velocity-- which
we'll actually cancel out

00:11:50.290 --> 00:11:51.490
in a moment.

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:54.450
But let's do it in
a systematic way--

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:58.640
and afterwards, we want the
velocity to decrease, linearly,

00:11:58.640 --> 00:11:59.440
in time.

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:05.180
I simply defined this
parameter, delta prime,

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:06.940
to be a solution
of this equation.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:09.430
So this is a well
defined quantity.

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:13.740
And the laser detuning--
which, I've broken my laser

00:12:13.740 --> 00:12:16.470
to change its detuning
as a function of time--

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:20.790
is now this nominal detuning
minus the Doppler shift

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:24.400
due to the velocity
of the atoms.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.150
I'm really solving the
problem backwards for you.

00:12:27.150 --> 00:12:32.040
I first decide which should
be the velocity trajectory

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:34.650
of the atoms-- how should
the atoms slow down.

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:39.090
And then, I define what
is the detuning which

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:40.910
will result in that.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:43.290
That's the easier
way to understand it.

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:44.890
Of course, if you
pick this detuning,

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:46.790
the atoms will exactly do that.

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:49.900
OK.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:54.660
But now what we're
doing is the following.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:13:01.200
This is sort of the
acceleration and the velocity

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:03.810
we want the atom to have.

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:07.820
But there may be some
atoms in the beam which

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:09.760
do not have this velocity.

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:13.210
They deviate from this
velocity with v prime.

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:15.810
So the goal of
cooling would now be

00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:20.750
to reduce v prime to 0 to
make all the atoms follow

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:22.700
the trajectory we have
designed for them.

00:13:25.551 --> 00:13:26.050
OK.

00:13:26.050 --> 00:13:29.730
Many words, many definitions.

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:31.267
Now we can simply
substitute what

00:13:31.267 --> 00:13:32.870
we have defined
into the equation.

00:13:32.870 --> 00:13:34.120
And we get a wonderful result.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:44.040
So we take equation
one, which was

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:48.270
the equation for
the light force.

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:50.210
And we put all
those definitions,

00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:56.290
which I went to great lengths
to explain to you, into it.

00:13:56.290 --> 00:14:01.040
And we get this result.

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:04.690
It's just that the detuning has
been expressed by delta prime,

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:07.970
and the velocity by this
difference velocity v prime.

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:10.426
It's pure mathematical
substitution.

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:16.962
But now comes the
important point

00:14:16.962 --> 00:14:20.410
that we want to describe
everything, now,

00:14:20.410 --> 00:14:23.170
in the decelerating frame.

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:26.550
The atoms are meant to
decelerate with a deceleration

00:14:26.550 --> 00:14:27.446
a.

00:14:27.446 --> 00:14:29.070
And you know, from
classical mechanics,

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:31.340
if you describe something
in a decelerating frame,

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:34.890
you have to add a
fictitious force.

00:14:34.890 --> 00:14:39.250
This fictitious force, since
the acceleration is constant,

00:14:39.250 --> 00:14:40.335
is a constant force.

00:14:43.330 --> 00:14:47.440
But I'm expressing it, now,
by the other parameters.

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:49.490
We've chosen our acceleration.

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:51.520
We've chosen the
detuning, delta prime,

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:54.180
that-- everything is
sort of connected.

00:14:54.180 --> 00:14:59.170
And this is just a way to
use the correct-- the most

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:03.600
easiest units, or the
correct parametrization,

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:05.010
for this constant force.

00:15:07.530 --> 00:15:10.660
So I have done-- and the
important thing for you

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.160
is, this equation is exact.

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:18.000
It's exact for an arbitrary
velocity v prime of the atoms.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:19.310
So let me just summarize.

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:21.440
I've taken the
spontaneous light force.

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:23.650
I've given you a
bunch of definitions,

00:15:23.650 --> 00:15:25.200
what delta prime is.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:28.780
That's how you
program your laser.

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:32.090
But then, in the
decelerating frame,

00:15:32.090 --> 00:15:33.900
we need a fictitious force.

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:39.150
And this is nothing else than
a mathematically exact rewrite

00:15:39.150 --> 00:15:41.840
of the spontaneous light force
in the decelerating frame.

00:15:49.070 --> 00:15:55.620
But now what happens is--
we had a decelerating--

00:15:55.620 --> 00:15:58.990
we had a light force where,
because we assume the laser is

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:01.180
counterpropagating,
there's a minus sign.

00:16:01.180 --> 00:16:04.960
The fictitious force
has a plus sign.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:11.480
And that means that we
can-- and if v prime is 0,

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:13.060
the force is 0.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:17.970
So we can now make a Taylor
expansion for small v prime.

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:22.980
So we have, again, a viscous
force, a friction force.

00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:25.990
And it turns out that
this friction coefficient

00:16:25.990 --> 00:16:30.810
for beam deceleration is
exactly 1/2 what we got before,

00:16:30.810 --> 00:16:32.270
for molasses.

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:34.320
But it's clear we
have one laser beam.

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:37.800
Whereas in molasses,
we had two laser beams.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:40.740
If you ask, what is
the heating, well,

00:16:40.740 --> 00:16:43.340
if you have one laser beam
and not two laser beams,

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:46.940
the heating described by the
momentum diffusion coefficient

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:48.280
is also just 1/2.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:53.090
One beam heats exactly half
of what we got for two beams.

00:16:53.090 --> 00:16:56.060
And therefore, the
temperature, which

00:16:56.060 --> 00:16:59.660
characterizes the width of
the velocity distribution

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:02.900
in the frame of the
decelerating atoms

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:05.849
is exactly the Doppler
temperature we had before.

00:17:05.849 --> 00:17:08.089
Because the two
factors of 1/2 cancel.

00:17:16.140 --> 00:17:18.420
So now I have given
you-- and I hope

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:22.390
you take some pleasure
in it-- an example where

00:17:22.390 --> 00:17:24.670
the laser cooling for
a two-level system

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:26.210
is exactly described.

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:27.829
There's only a single beam.

00:17:27.829 --> 00:17:30.250
And the Doppler limit
is the exact solution.

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:32.720
I've not made any
approximation other

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:35.860
than assuming I have a
two-level system for which

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:38.900
the spontaneous light force has
the expression we've derived.

00:17:41.551 --> 00:17:42.050
OK.

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:45.520
I know, even with
my explanation,

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:47.680
you have to read through
it once or twice.

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:50.720
Because I made a
few substitutions.

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:53.560
And you really have to
digest them at your own pace.

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:57.860
So let me give you a summary of
what we have done graphically.

00:17:57.860 --> 00:18:01.080
One laser beam scatters light.

00:18:01.080 --> 00:18:04.280
And it is this Lorentzian.

00:18:04.280 --> 00:18:06.499
And it's a negative
Lorentzian because we

00:18:06.499 --> 00:18:07.790
have a counterpropagating beam.

00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:10.000
We push the atoms into
the negative direction,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.810
they fly in the
positive direction.

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:16.550
But by going-- by
chirping the laser,

00:18:16.550 --> 00:18:23.040
by going into the
decelerating frame,

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:26.960
the force doesn't go to 0.

00:18:26.960 --> 00:18:29.260
I had to add an offset.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:32.240
And this offset is
the fictitious force

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:35.540
due to the transformation
of the decelerating frame.

00:18:35.540 --> 00:18:40.500
And now you realize
that this force-- and it

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:44.230
is the correct force in the
decelerating frame-- has two 0

00:18:44.230 --> 00:18:45.700
crossings.

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:50.330
One is a stable point, and
one is an unstable point.

00:18:50.330 --> 00:18:54.790
And the stable point says, if
an atom happens to be too fast,

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:56.400
it gets a correcting force.

00:18:56.400 --> 00:18:58.410
And this is like a lock point.

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:00.230
It has a stable lock point.

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:06.790
All the atoms which did not have
the correct velocity we wanted

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:10.660
them to have, they are sort of
sucked into this lock point,

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:14.130
and eventually, will
pile up at a huge peak

00:19:14.130 --> 00:19:15.940
at this nominal velocity.

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:17.950
And the width of
this peak is simply

00:19:17.950 --> 00:19:21.560
described by the Doppler limit.

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:25.310
Before I take your
questions, let

00:19:25.310 --> 00:19:31.175
me show you what happens
in the two frames.

00:19:36.720 --> 00:19:39.350
This is v prime.

00:19:39.350 --> 00:19:46.340
This is the velocity in
the decelerating frame.

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:52.190
And let's say our
initial velocity is this.

00:19:52.190 --> 00:19:58.460
So what happens now is all
the atoms within the atoms

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:04.810
are decelerated towards
v prime equals 0.

00:20:04.810 --> 00:20:09.030
The friction force puts
them to v prime equals 0.

00:20:09.030 --> 00:20:11.950
But since we are in
a decelerating frame,

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:15.310
in the absence of the laser,
the whole Maxwell-Boltzmann

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.960
distribution is
just shifted-- not

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:19.800
because the velocity
of the atoms

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:22.460
changed-- because we are
in a decelerating frame

00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:25.230
and we are accelerating
away from the atoms.

00:20:25.230 --> 00:20:28.660
And what I just described for
you is the following-- that,

00:20:28.660 --> 00:20:32.650
at v prime equals 0, we
have our friction force.

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:36.460
And the atomic
distribution in this frame

00:20:36.460 --> 00:20:38.210
is now pushed through.

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:41.420
And everything which goes
through this resonant region

00:20:41.420 --> 00:20:43.130
is sort of collected.

00:20:43.130 --> 00:20:50.230
And you have a peak which is
piling up at v prime equals 0.

00:20:50.230 --> 00:20:55.630
Probably, it's easier--
but mathematically,

00:20:55.630 --> 00:20:57.490
I needed the
decelerating frame--

00:20:57.490 --> 00:20:59.750
if you use the
following picture.

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:03.710
And just think of this beam
slowing I explained to you.

00:21:03.710 --> 00:21:05.740
If you just switched
on a laser here,

00:21:05.740 --> 00:21:08.315
you would just burn a hole
into the velocity distribution

00:21:08.315 --> 00:21:10.160
and pile up the atoms.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:11.700
But now you sweep.

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:14.820
And when you sweep, you take
the peak, push it further.

00:21:14.820 --> 00:21:16.180
It gets a bigger peak here.

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:17.380
Push it further.

00:21:17.380 --> 00:21:19.750
So eventually, what
you're doing is,

00:21:19.750 --> 00:21:22.550
by chirping the laser
in the correct way

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:25.060
with the correct laser
power and all that,

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:29.020
you're just pushing
the atoms all out.

00:21:29.020 --> 00:21:31.690
And eventually,
they are piled up

00:21:31.690 --> 00:21:35.840
in a narrow distribution which
is defined by the time when you

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:38.280
just switch off your laser beam.

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:41.360
So one chirp of the laser,
from an initial detuning

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:45.430
in the lab frame to a final
detuning in the lab frame,

00:21:45.430 --> 00:21:49.950
will just sweep out the whole
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution.

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:52.400
And if you suddenly
switch off the laser,

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:56.580
you have frozen in a velocity
distribution which is exactly

00:21:56.580 --> 00:21:58.535
described by the Doppler limit.

00:22:04.180 --> 00:22:06.290
So what is easier to
understand-- molasses

00:22:06.290 --> 00:22:12.050
with two beams, or beam
slowing with a single beam?

00:22:12.050 --> 00:22:14.140
I think molasses is
easier, because everything

00:22:14.140 --> 00:22:15.330
happens in the lab frame.

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:16.670
But think about it.

00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:23.275
It's a nice example for which no
approximations have to be made.

00:22:23.275 --> 00:22:23.775
Questions?

00:22:28.520 --> 00:22:30.310
Yes, Nancy.

00:22:30.310 --> 00:22:31.980
AUDIENCE: It's not
really obvious to me

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:36.450
how, in this mathematics,
we are choosing

00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:39.324
a time-dependent
detuning as opposed

00:22:39.324 --> 00:22:41.719
to a time-dependent
deceleration.

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:49.900
PROFESSOR: The way I
presented it logically, we

00:22:49.900 --> 00:22:52.950
said we want a certain
acceleration to happen.

00:22:52.950 --> 00:23:00.250
And then, we provide our laser
that k/kv is the Doppler shift.

00:23:00.250 --> 00:23:04.620
ka is how the Doppler shift
changes as a function of time.

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:09.330
And we chirp our laser
exactly in frequency

00:23:09.330 --> 00:23:12.840
with a chirp which is ka.

00:23:12.840 --> 00:23:17.950
So in other words, I started
to define a constant a.

00:23:17.950 --> 00:23:20.890
And that would require
that the laser is now

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:23.100
chirped in a linear way.

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:25.500
I could have started the
other around and said, hey,

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:28.220
let's assume we chirp the
laser in a linear way.

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:30.740
And then, we do
corresponding substitutions.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:33.260
And the result
would be the same.

00:23:33.260 --> 00:23:35.715
AUDIENCE: No, actually,
like if we did not

00:23:35.715 --> 00:23:39.760
want to have a detuning
which was time-dependent,

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:42.670
would we have gotten--
we still have a force.

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:44.657
And that force would
have been just changing.

00:23:44.657 --> 00:23:46.740
PROFESSOR: Well then, it's
more complicated, yeah.

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:49.480
Then, you have to integrate
a differential equation.

00:23:49.480 --> 00:23:53.200
But what happened
is the following.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:57.300
What I've done is, by defining
the acceleration and then

00:23:57.300 --> 00:24:02.570
the chirp, I have the situation
that, in the reference

00:24:02.570 --> 00:24:06.800
frame of the decelerating
atoms, the detuning is constant.

00:24:06.800 --> 00:24:10.020
So usually, you go to
a decelerating frame

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:12.100
if something else simplifies.

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:16.670
And what simplifies is that,
in the frame of the atom,

00:24:16.670 --> 00:24:18.910
the laser detuning is constant.

00:24:18.910 --> 00:24:22.770
So you can also say the frame
in which the atoms decelerate is

00:24:22.770 --> 00:24:27.900
exactly the frame in which
the chirp has disappeared.

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:30.870
Because the decelerating
frame compensates

00:24:30.870 --> 00:24:33.810
the chirp with a
linearly varying,

00:24:33.810 --> 00:24:35.600
time varying Doppler shift.

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:42.020
OK.

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:45.860
But the physics, I
think, is really--

00:24:45.860 --> 00:24:49.160
the moment you have a force
which has a 0 crossing,

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:50.380
it's a lock point.

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:52.020
You determine the slope.

00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:54.260
And alpha, together with
the momentum diffusion,

00:24:54.260 --> 00:24:55.650
gives you the final temperature.

00:24:55.650 --> 00:24:58.520
So I hope you enjoy that it's
actually the same physics--

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:00.910
exactly the same
physics-- we discussed,

00:25:00.910 --> 00:25:03.700
with some approximation
for molasses.

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:09.560
OK.

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:14.230
We had a discussion last time
about, we have the force,

00:25:14.230 --> 00:25:16.720
we find exactly what
happens to the atoms.

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:20.850
But we may have to think
about it in different ways

00:25:20.850 --> 00:25:26.020
to figure out where the
kinetic energy goes from.

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:29.700
And I think we mentioned it
already, in the last class,

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:33.960
that what happens is you have
a red-detuned laser, which is,

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:36.130
the photons are absorbed.

00:25:36.130 --> 00:25:40.200
But the atom is scattering
light in all directions.

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:43.000
And so if you go
at 90 degrees, you

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:44.920
don't have a linear
Doppler shift.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:48.080
If you go forward-backward
with the same probability--

00:25:48.080 --> 00:25:51.890
a symmetric pattern-- the
Doppler shift averages to 0.

00:25:51.890 --> 00:25:56.810
So on average, you emit
photons which are on resonance.

00:25:56.810 --> 00:26:00.880
And therefore, every time
you scatter a photon,

00:26:00.880 --> 00:26:05.270
you radiate away
the energy which

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:06.530
is equal to the Doppler shift.

00:26:11.300 --> 00:26:14.000
That means, initially, when
the Doppler shift is huge,

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:17.480
each photon transports
away a lot of energy.

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:20.910
And the slower the atoms
are, the less a photon

00:26:20.910 --> 00:26:22.570
transports away.

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:23.870
But that makes sense.

00:26:23.870 --> 00:26:25.800
If you have a huge
velocity and you

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:29.570
subtract h bar k, the
momentum of the photon,

00:26:29.570 --> 00:26:33.380
the kinetic energy is
quadratic in velocity.

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:37.300
You know, h bar k, the
momentum transfer of a photon,

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:40.260
takes out more kinetic
energy the faster

00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:42.550
the velocity of the atoms is.

00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:44.445
So everything makes
sense and is consistent.

00:26:52.450 --> 00:26:53.140
OK.

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:58.570
Let's go from the-- we
started with two beams.

00:26:58.570 --> 00:27:02.080
We just discussed one
beam, chirped slowing.

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:06.360
And let's go now to what most
of you use in the laboratory--

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:08.440
namely, six beams.

00:27:08.440 --> 00:27:11.210
You want to cool in x, y, z.

00:27:11.210 --> 00:27:13.670
So you have
one-dimensional molasses

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:17.130
with two beams times 3.

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:22.610
So in the limit that
the intensity is low,

00:27:22.610 --> 00:27:26.140
you just add up all the forces.

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:28.710
You say each beam has a
spontaneous light force.

00:27:28.710 --> 00:27:31.618
And you add the six
spontaneous light forces up.

00:27:34.610 --> 00:27:38.110
At low intensity-- and you
have to take my word for it--

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:41.150
you can ignore all the
interference effect

00:27:41.150 --> 00:27:43.280
between the beams.

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:47.760
They can actually lead to
very interesting effects.

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:51.530
I will give you at least a taste
of what will happen-- actually,

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:55.610
a pretty good taste-- what
happens at higher power.

00:27:55.610 --> 00:27:57.495
We need the traced atom picture.

00:27:57.495 --> 00:28:01.155
And we'll discuss how
the stimulated force

00:28:01.155 --> 00:28:02.155
can be used for cooling.

00:28:04.750 --> 00:28:07.180
But if you don't have
a two-level system,

00:28:07.180 --> 00:28:10.450
you have sigma plus
sigma minus transitions

00:28:10.450 --> 00:28:17.270
and the beams interfere, you get
spatially varying polarizations

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:19.350
of your interference
patterns, and then you

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.240
have much [INAUDIBLE] physics.

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:26.120
But in the simplest case
of a two-level system,

00:28:26.120 --> 00:28:28.150
there is a regime
at low intensity

00:28:28.150 --> 00:28:32.510
where you can simply take the
equations we got for molasses

00:28:32.510 --> 00:28:33.715
and apply them to XYZ.

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:41.660
I put, on the website, a nice
handout, a review paper by Bill

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:46.560
Phillips, who is discussing 1D
molasses versus 3D molasses,

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:48.480
and if you enjoy
it, you can read

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:52.400
how numerical factors
of 1 or 2 or 3

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:55.920
now appear in the
friction coefficient,

00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:57.650
in the heating
coefficient, and how

00:28:57.650 --> 00:28:59.860
they affect the
final temperature.

00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:03.510
But you got the full [INAUDIBLE]
concepts and the correct idea

00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:04.930
for one dimension molasses.

00:29:11.290 --> 00:29:22.310
Now, let me give you
an outlook for what

00:29:22.310 --> 00:29:24.250
we will be doing next week.

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:28.790
Next week, we want to
understand the following-- what

00:29:28.790 --> 00:29:31.170
happens to the
friction coefficient

00:29:31.170 --> 00:29:34.070
when you increase the power?

00:29:34.070 --> 00:29:38.190
Well, you remember when
we have red-detuned light,

00:29:38.190 --> 00:29:43.670
then we had one Lorentzian,
another Lorentzian.

00:29:43.670 --> 00:29:45.770
The slope was
negative, and negative

00:29:45.770 --> 00:29:49.480
means positive
friction, we cool.

00:29:49.480 --> 00:29:51.840
And if you put
more power into it,

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:55.140
the linear slope increases,
and for low power,

00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:57.620
the friction coefficient is
proportional to the laser

00:29:57.620 --> 00:29:59.540
intensity.

00:29:59.540 --> 00:30:01.850
But now look what happens.

00:30:01.850 --> 00:30:10.330
If you approach saturation,
then the friction

00:30:10.330 --> 00:30:16.680
is not only saturating, it
suddenly changes the sign,

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:19.230
and this is qualitatively new.

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:22.050
And you should a little
bit wonder about it.

00:30:22.050 --> 00:30:25.280
Wasn't the reason why we
have cooling that you have

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:28.140
a laser which is red-detuned?

00:30:28.140 --> 00:30:30.440
And the photon which is
spontaneously emitted

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:33.800
is on resonance, and this
is the energy difference.

00:30:33.800 --> 00:30:37.470
But now I'm telling
you, at high intensity,

00:30:37.470 --> 00:30:40.210
it's not the red-detuned
laser which cools,

00:30:40.210 --> 00:30:44.020
it's the blue-detuned laser.

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:45.660
So you should wonder about it.

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:49.040
There is really something
new to be learned.

