00:54:14.310 --> 00:54:17.140
you want to think about
it when you describe

00:54:17.140 --> 00:54:19.690
the stimulated light force.

00:54:19.690 --> 00:54:23.660
And I mentioned already, it is
the dressed atom picture which

00:54:23.660 --> 00:54:29.240
will help me to give you the
physical picture behind if you

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:32.580
have strong laser beams,
why blue-detuned light cools

00:54:32.580 --> 00:54:34.360
and not red-detuned light.

00:54:34.360 --> 00:54:37.230
So you should be motivated now
to learn about the dressed atom

00:54:37.230 --> 00:54:39.040
picture.

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:41.910
But first, I have
to say it's not

00:54:41.910 --> 00:54:44.530
anything new, what
I'm teaching you.

00:54:47.060 --> 00:54:50.180
It has exactly the
same physics in it

00:54:50.180 --> 00:54:52.940
as the optical Bloch equations.

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:56.620
It's just that the optical
Bloch equations are

00:54:56.620 --> 00:54:59.070
often more complicated,
and they don't

00:54:59.070 --> 00:55:00.880
provide the clear insight.

00:55:00.880 --> 00:55:03.305
And the reason is the following.

00:55:03.305 --> 00:55:05.690
Often when you describe
a physical phenomenon,

00:55:05.690 --> 00:55:09.850
you can choose one basis set, or
you can use another basis set.

00:55:09.850 --> 00:55:11.950
But if you're in
the wrong basis,

00:55:11.950 --> 00:55:15.180
you get the correct results,
but in the wrong basis,

00:55:15.180 --> 00:55:17.900
you just can't describe
the physics easily.

00:55:17.900 --> 00:55:21.010
So in other words, with
the dressed atom picture,

00:55:21.010 --> 00:55:25.430
I want to introduce dressed
atom states for you which

00:55:25.430 --> 00:55:29.160
are no longer the ground
state and the excited state.

00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:33.310
I want to treat the
atoms dressed up

00:55:33.310 --> 00:55:36.360
by the laser beam,
which is one mode

00:55:36.360 --> 00:55:38.370
of the electromagnetic field.

00:55:38.370 --> 00:55:41.690
So the atoms, together
with this one laser beam,

00:55:41.690 --> 00:55:44.980
will be partially excited,
partially in the ground state.

00:55:44.980 --> 00:55:47.730
And this partially
excited atoms, this

00:55:47.730 --> 00:55:49.980
is the dressed atom basis.

00:55:49.980 --> 00:55:54.990
But if you think in
terms of those states,

00:55:54.990 --> 00:55:57.180
you have a much easier
way to formulate

00:55:57.180 --> 00:56:00.560
certain physical processes,
exactly processes

00:56:00.560 --> 00:56:02.080
where you have high laser power.

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:04.120
At low laser power,
the dress states

00:56:04.120 --> 00:56:06.280
are identical to
the naked states

00:56:06.280 --> 00:56:07.730
to the ground and
excited states.

00:56:07.730 --> 00:56:11.810
But at high laser power,
at infinite laser power,

00:56:11.810 --> 00:56:16.240
the two dressed states are the
symmetric and anti-symmetric

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:19.330
equal superposition of
grounded and excited state.

00:56:19.330 --> 00:56:22.600
So that's what we
want to describe now.

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:27.180
So the difference to the
Optical Bloch Equation

00:56:27.180 --> 00:56:29.290
is that we are
now really looking

00:56:29.290 --> 00:56:31.360
for the combined
state of the atom

00:56:31.360 --> 00:56:34.530
in the electromagnetic field.

00:56:34.530 --> 00:56:43.130
So what we want to do is--
this is sort of our picture

00:56:43.130 --> 00:56:44.310
that we have.

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:46.680
This is our Hamiltonian.

00:56:46.680 --> 00:56:50.310
We have the atom
interacting with the vacuum

00:56:50.310 --> 00:56:52.560
through spontaneous
emission with a reservoir

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:54.340
of empty modes.

00:56:54.340 --> 00:56:58.110
But now, it also interacts
with the laser beam.

00:56:58.110 --> 00:57:00.820
And you remember when we
did the master equation,

00:57:00.820 --> 00:57:02.530
we looked sort of at this.

00:57:02.530 --> 00:57:05.070
We derived a master
equation for this.

00:57:05.070 --> 00:57:07.740
And then we added
in the unitary time

00:57:07.740 --> 00:57:09.830
evolution due to laser beam.

00:57:09.830 --> 00:57:12.030
But what we want to
do now is we want

00:57:12.030 --> 00:57:16.790
to first take care of the
atom and the laser beam

00:57:16.790 --> 00:57:19.820
almost exactly in an
exact diagonalization.

00:57:19.820 --> 00:57:22.170
And once we have
re-diagonalized that,

00:57:22.170 --> 00:57:26.030
we have now eigenstates which
we call the dressed states.

00:57:26.030 --> 00:57:29.640
Then we allow not the
ground and excited state.

00:57:29.640 --> 00:57:33.457
We then allow the dressed
states to emit into the vacuum.

00:57:33.457 --> 00:57:35.540
And this is the formulation
we want to obtain now.

00:57:47.130 --> 00:57:50.430
Let me make one
comment before I go

00:57:50.430 --> 00:57:54.930
through a few simple equation,
and that's the following.

00:57:54.930 --> 00:57:59.190
If I want to treat this
system almost exactly,

00:57:59.190 --> 00:58:02.290
I have two choices.

00:58:02.290 --> 00:58:04.650
I use a strong laser beam.

00:58:04.650 --> 00:58:08.190
So I could, as we have
discussed several times,

00:58:08.190 --> 00:58:11.990
simply use the time dependent
external electric field.

00:58:11.990 --> 00:58:15.550
The laser beam is E0
times cosine omega t.

00:58:15.550 --> 00:58:18.780
And I just introduced
that in the Hamiltonian.

00:58:18.780 --> 00:58:21.870
And you can get
everything I describe now

00:58:21.870 --> 00:58:23.500
for you out of this Hamiltonian.

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:28.860
However, there is
an alternative way.

00:58:28.860 --> 00:58:34.980
And this one is I simply
assume that the laser beam is

00:58:34.980 --> 00:58:37.240
described by the
fully quantized field.

00:58:37.240 --> 00:58:39.070
And I use the fog state.

00:58:39.070 --> 00:58:42.530
I just assume N, the number
of photons, is very big.

00:58:47.570 --> 00:58:49.720
And this is, at least
for that purpose,

00:58:49.720 --> 00:58:52.880
a valid description
of the laser beam.

00:58:52.880 --> 00:58:55.810
So what happens is you really
want to look through that.

00:58:55.810 --> 00:58:58.380
I've really learned
a lot by comparing

00:58:58.380 --> 00:59:00.860
the purely classical
treatment of the laser beam

00:59:00.860 --> 00:59:03.590
and the fully quantized
description of the laser beam.

00:59:03.590 --> 00:59:04.700
The results are the same.

00:59:04.700 --> 00:59:07.150
They are Absolutely identical.

00:59:07.150 --> 00:59:10.570
And what you will see is, by
a bunch of approximations,

00:59:10.570 --> 00:59:13.880
we reduce the total
Hamiltonian to-- I've

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:16.260
seen it many times--
a two by two matrix.

00:59:16.260 --> 00:59:18.330
And whether you start
with the classical field

00:59:18.330 --> 00:59:20.540
or whether you start with
the fully quantized field,

00:59:20.540 --> 00:59:22.520
if you make the
right approximation,

00:59:22.520 --> 00:59:25.010
you get the same
two by two matrix.

00:59:25.010 --> 00:59:26.920
But there's a difference.

00:59:26.920 --> 00:59:29.720
This Hamiltonian is
time independent.

00:59:29.720 --> 00:59:33.870
a dagger a, time
independent Hamiltonian.

00:59:33.870 --> 00:59:38.430
If you take a classical field,
which is cosine omega lt,

00:59:38.430 --> 00:59:41.130
you don't have a time
independent Hamiltonian.

00:59:41.130 --> 00:59:43.520
You have a driven system,
and your wave function

00:59:43.520 --> 00:59:45.830
has an external time dependence.

00:59:45.830 --> 00:59:49.040
The laser beam is driving
the wave function.

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:51.390
So in other words,
you have two choices

00:59:51.390 --> 00:59:53.870
when you want to describe
how an atom interacts

00:59:53.870 --> 00:59:55.180
with a strong laser beam.

00:59:55.180 --> 00:59:58.545
You can use the fully quantized
field, which is conceptionally

00:59:58.545 --> 01:00:00.610
a little bit more
complicated, because we've

01:00:00.610 --> 01:00:02.290
quantized the
electromagnetic field.

01:00:02.290 --> 01:00:04.780
But then everything
is time independent,

01:00:04.780 --> 01:00:07.880
and everything I do
here is really easy.

01:00:07.880 --> 01:00:09.600
I can go over it
now in five minutes,

01:00:09.600 --> 01:00:12.120
and you understand everything.

