01:02:49.030 --> 01:02:52.300
And I used the dressed atom
picture and I got confused.

01:02:52.300 --> 01:02:54.540
So what happened
is the following.

01:02:54.540 --> 01:02:59.340
If you pick your right bases,
the description is simple.

01:02:59.340 --> 01:03:02.770
But simple means
if all the physics

01:03:02.770 --> 01:03:04.605
is your atom is in
one dressed state

01:03:04.605 --> 01:03:06.730
or the other dressed state,
and it does transitions

01:03:06.730 --> 01:03:09.270
between the dressed
states and that is easy,

01:03:09.270 --> 01:03:12.280
and this happens in the
limit of large detuning.

01:03:12.280 --> 01:03:14.190
But if you're in
the regime where

01:03:14.190 --> 01:03:17.130
coherences between the
dressed states matter.

01:03:17.130 --> 01:03:20.300
In other words, the density
matrix in the dressed state

01:03:20.300 --> 01:03:22.780
basis has now off
diagonal matrix element.

01:03:22.780 --> 01:03:25.340
The physics becomes
complicated again.

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:28.140
So in other words, what
I'm telling you is you

01:03:28.140 --> 01:03:33.170
are the best description
happens when we have a two level

01:03:33.170 --> 01:03:35.410
system, we always need
a two by two matrix.

01:03:35.410 --> 01:03:39.020
But if you pick the description
where the solution is diagonal,

01:03:39.020 --> 01:03:41.300
if you have to deal with
coherence, using coherence

01:03:41.300 --> 01:03:43.830
is coupled to population,
it's complicated.

01:03:43.830 --> 01:03:47.210
And there's some cases-- one is
the blue detuned lattice, which

01:03:47.210 --> 01:03:50.190
I encounter where you have to
consider the coherences to get

01:03:50.190 --> 01:03:51.530
the correct answer.

01:03:51.530 --> 01:03:55.730
And usually, also when
the laser beams are weak

01:03:55.730 --> 01:03:58.530
and on resonance, the
dressed atom picture

01:03:58.530 --> 01:04:01.340
is not providing any advantages.

01:04:01.340 --> 01:04:05.640
So you want to use the bare
picture for weak excitations.

01:04:05.640 --> 01:04:09.990
And yes, in the resonance
case, the dressed atom picture,

01:04:09.990 --> 01:04:11.900
if you're very
close to resonance,

01:04:11.900 --> 01:04:15.380
the dressed atom picture
gets more complicated.

01:04:15.380 --> 01:04:18.420
But to give you the answer in
something we have discussed,

01:04:18.420 --> 01:04:21.330
you know already that when
you drive an atom with a laser

01:04:21.330 --> 01:04:24.350
beam, you get the
Mollow triplet.

01:04:24.350 --> 01:04:28.120
And the Mollow
triplet shows you--

01:04:28.120 --> 01:04:32.010
I hope we can finish that
today-- shows you the energy

01:04:32.010 --> 01:04:33.980
splitting between the
dressed energy levels,

01:04:33.980 --> 01:04:35.520
between the dressed
energy levels.

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:38.500
But if the Mollow
triplet is not resolved

01:04:38.500 --> 01:04:41.940
because the generalized
Rabi frequency is small,

01:04:41.940 --> 01:04:45.280
then you're not resolving
your dressed atom levels.

01:04:45.280 --> 01:04:46.882
And then the dressed
atom level is not

01:04:46.882 --> 01:04:47.965
providing a big advantage.

01:04:52.520 --> 01:04:54.470
For certain problems,
the dressed atom picture

01:04:54.470 --> 01:04:57.450
will not help you.

01:04:57.450 --> 01:04:59.167
But I can reassure
you, and this is

01:04:59.167 --> 01:05:01.000
what I learned from
Jean Dalibard and Claude

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:03.330
Cohen-Tannoudji,
if you really look

01:05:03.330 --> 01:05:06.060
at the full matrix with the
off diagonal matrix append

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:09.590
and everything, you will always
find exactly the same solution.

01:05:16.100 --> 01:05:17.870
Anyway, we were
just writing down

01:05:17.870 --> 01:05:22.720
product states of the atoms
and the eigenfunctions

01:05:22.720 --> 01:05:24.900
of the Hamiltonian
for the light, which

01:05:24.900 --> 01:05:28.600
are fog states, number
states with N, L N plus 1.

01:05:28.600 --> 01:05:31.540
But the important thing
is now the following.

01:05:31.540 --> 01:05:35.535
In the limit of small
detuning, the ground state

01:05:35.535 --> 01:05:39.720
with N plus 1 photon is almost
degenerate with the excited

01:05:39.720 --> 01:05:41.190
state with N photons.

01:05:41.190 --> 01:05:44.720
And we call these two
states a manifold.

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:48.550
The manifold E of N. And
N is the photon number

01:05:48.550 --> 01:05:49.630
in the excited state.

01:05:53.620 --> 01:05:58.140
So what happens is, if you
look at all those states,

01:05:58.140 --> 01:06:01.740
they are grouped into manifolds.

01:06:01.740 --> 01:06:05.080
And the energy separation
between two manifolds

01:06:05.080 --> 01:06:12.320
is, of course, I go from N to N
plus 1, the energy of a photon.

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:16.550
So now I introduce the
atom laser coupling

01:06:16.550 --> 01:06:19.050
in the usual dipole
approximation.

01:06:19.050 --> 01:06:23.600
And what happens is, this
dipole approximation,

01:06:23.600 --> 01:06:28.530
this dipole light atom coupling
will couple, of course,

01:06:28.530 --> 01:06:31.020
ground and excited state.

01:06:31.020 --> 01:06:34.400
And it will, of course,
have a big effect

01:06:34.400 --> 01:06:37.220
when the energy
splitting is small.

01:06:37.220 --> 01:06:41.150
Well, you will see
that in the next line.

01:06:41.150 --> 01:06:45.230
But we have the co and
counter rotating terms.

01:06:45.230 --> 01:06:49.910
This dipole Hamiltonian will
also couple the ground state

01:06:49.910 --> 01:06:53.040
to the excited state
in the other manifold.

01:06:53.040 --> 01:06:58.150
This is the off resonant
term, which will be neglect.

01:06:58.150 --> 01:06:59.760
So here are the
equations for that.

01:07:02.830 --> 01:07:06.530
Our electric field is, of
course, a plus a dagger.

01:07:06.530 --> 01:07:09.530
The dipole operator is that.

01:07:09.530 --> 01:07:15.210
And if you take what is in
front of the electric field

01:07:15.210 --> 01:07:19.390
and define this as the
coupling constant, g,

01:07:19.390 --> 01:07:24.950
we have what I just told
you, that within a manifold,

01:07:24.950 --> 01:07:26.980
the ground state
with N plus 1 photons

01:07:26.980 --> 01:07:31.800
is coupled to the excited
state with N photons.

01:07:31.800 --> 01:07:33.560
g is simply the
coupling constant,

01:07:33.560 --> 01:07:37.770
which all parameters have
been included in that.

01:07:37.770 --> 01:07:41.000
But then, because of the matrix
element of a or a dagger,

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:42.980
we have the square
root of N plus 1.

01:07:45.500 --> 01:07:50.440
OK, so what we are now doing is
we are going with this coupling

01:07:50.440 --> 01:07:53.020
within a manifold, which
is strong because the two

01:07:53.020 --> 01:07:54.760
levels are energetically close.

01:07:54.760 --> 01:07:58.270
And we will neglect the
non-resonant couplings

01:07:58.270 --> 01:07:59.810
to the other manifolds.

01:07:59.810 --> 01:08:02.027
And that's just another
way of doing, again,

01:08:02.027 --> 01:08:03.360
the rotating wave approximation.

01:08:10.640 --> 01:08:13.920
Now, when we describe an atom
in the laser field and the atom

01:08:13.920 --> 01:08:16.420
scatters light, or
we have a laser beam,

01:08:16.420 --> 01:08:19.340
and I have to tell you,
when we have a laser beam,

01:08:19.340 --> 01:08:23.069
we don't provide exactly
N atom, N photons.

01:08:23.069 --> 01:08:25.279
The laser beam is
in a coherent state.

01:08:25.279 --> 01:08:27.890
And there are
Poissonian fluctuations.

01:08:27.890 --> 01:08:31.600
But now, we do the next
approximation, namely we

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:34.670
say when N is
large, then delta N

01:08:34.670 --> 01:08:38.450
can be neglected
with regard to N.

01:08:38.450 --> 01:08:41.770
Then at least for the
range of important photon

01:08:41.770 --> 01:08:45.819
numbers for the problem, this
coupling becomes independent

01:08:45.819 --> 01:08:50.550
of N. And we simply take the
average number of photons

01:08:50.550 --> 01:08:58.090
in our laser beam and define
now an electric field, which

01:08:58.090 --> 01:09:01.859
is independent of N.

01:09:01.859 --> 01:09:03.920
And the product with
the dipole operator

01:09:03.920 --> 01:09:07.930
of the atom, that's what
we call the Rabi frequency.

01:09:07.930 --> 01:09:12.380
So at that point, we introduce
a classical electric field

01:09:12.380 --> 01:09:15.210
through this definition, and
therefore, the dressed atom

01:09:15.210 --> 01:09:15.779
picture.

01:09:15.779 --> 01:09:19.660
Also, we start with the fully
quantized Hamiltonian is now

01:09:19.660 --> 01:09:24.160
identical to the classical
field with this electric field

01:09:24.160 --> 01:09:24.660
amplitude.

01:09:29.600 --> 01:09:32.960
But what we have gained is
we could discuss everything

01:09:32.960 --> 01:09:35.640
in a time independent picture.

01:09:35.640 --> 01:09:39.670
And now, I promised you,
we'll go back to a two

01:09:39.670 --> 01:09:42.120
by two matrix, which you
have seen many times.

01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:44.569
It's a two level system.

01:09:44.569 --> 01:09:47.720
We have the detuning.

01:09:47.720 --> 01:09:50.450
We are in the rotating frame.

01:09:50.450 --> 01:09:55.400
So that means the ground and
excited state with N and N

01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:59.070
minus 1 photons have
the same energy.

01:09:59.070 --> 01:10:02.410
But if we have a detuning,
there is a difference

01:10:02.410 --> 01:10:04.400
whether we excite the
atom or whether we

01:10:04.400 --> 01:10:06.060
put a photon in the laser field.

01:10:06.060 --> 01:10:08.210
But you have seen
that many, many times.

01:10:08.210 --> 01:10:10.240
And the coupling
is now described

01:10:10.240 --> 01:10:13.130
by the Rabi frequency.

01:10:13.130 --> 01:10:17.590
So that's kind of
our typical two level

01:10:17.590 --> 01:10:20.680
system where the two levels
[INAUDIBLE] the rotating frame,

01:10:20.680 --> 01:10:23.410
everything is time independent.

01:10:23.410 --> 01:10:28.860
The two levels are split,
and they are coupled.

01:10:28.860 --> 01:10:32.760
And well, how many times have
you seen the solution of two

01:10:32.760 --> 01:10:35.210
by two matrix?

01:10:35.210 --> 01:10:38.820
The solution is that
the coupling is now

01:10:38.820 --> 01:10:40.450
increasing the splitting.

01:10:40.450 --> 01:10:42.100
The splitting between
the two levels

01:10:42.100 --> 01:10:45.000
is, again, the generalized
Rabi frequency,

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:48.830
which you have seen
many, many times.

01:10:48.830 --> 01:10:51.410
But now we want to really
get the wave function.

01:10:51.410 --> 01:10:54.920
We want to get something out
of the dressed atom picture.

01:10:54.920 --> 01:10:57.830
And that's the following.

01:10:57.830 --> 01:11:01.760
We started out with the
bare states-- ground

01:11:01.760 --> 01:11:04.700
state with N plus 1, excited
state with N photons.

01:11:04.700 --> 01:11:09.880
And the two by two matrix
after the diagonalization

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:12.260
is now a linear
combination of those.

01:11:12.260 --> 01:11:14.870
And it's convenient to use
sine theta, cosine theta,

01:11:14.870 --> 01:11:18.920
because then the states are
automatically normalized.

01:11:18.920 --> 01:11:21.780
If I introduce the
solution is now

01:11:21.780 --> 01:11:24.790
that the angle theta is
given by this equation,

01:11:24.790 --> 01:11:28.290
that's just the solution
for the two by two matrix.

01:11:28.290 --> 01:11:32.530
And the physical picture,
which we have obtained,

01:11:32.530 --> 01:11:33.285
is the following.

01:11:38.420 --> 01:11:43.190
If this here is the energy
of the excited state with N

01:11:43.190 --> 01:11:49.720
photons, I've just sort of drawn
this as a reference parallel.

01:11:49.720 --> 01:11:52.800
But now I want to draw it
as a function of the laser

01:11:52.800 --> 01:11:54.660
frequency.

01:11:54.660 --> 01:11:57.560
Well, the ground state
with N plus 1 photons

01:11:57.560 --> 01:12:01.050
has exactly the same
energy on resonance.

01:12:01.050 --> 01:12:04.980
But if the photon is more
energetic then this state,

01:12:04.980 --> 01:12:07.870
because it has N plus 1
photons versus n photons

01:12:07.870 --> 01:12:11.480
if the photon is more energetic
than a resonant photon,

01:12:11.480 --> 01:12:12.850
this state has higher energy.

01:12:12.850 --> 01:12:15.160
And here, it has lower energy.

01:12:15.160 --> 01:12:17.610
In other words, we
have now a level

01:12:17.610 --> 01:12:21.300
crossing between
the two bare states.

01:12:21.300 --> 01:12:23.500
But a level crossing
with interaction

01:12:23.500 --> 01:12:25.510
turns into an avoided crossing.

01:12:25.510 --> 01:12:27.450
And the solution which
we have just derived

01:12:27.450 --> 01:12:29.850
are the blue curves.

01:12:29.850 --> 01:12:32.830
And if I go far
away from resonance,

01:12:32.830 --> 01:12:37.240
this behavior here,
which is perturbative,

01:12:37.240 --> 01:12:40.970
is nothing else than
the AC Stark shift.

01:12:40.970 --> 01:12:43.820
So this is exactly what we
have discussed at this point.

01:12:47.970 --> 01:12:51.380
Now, let's get some
mileage out of it.

01:12:51.380 --> 01:12:54.862
And we will talk
about light forces.

01:12:54.862 --> 01:12:55.945
That's really interesting.

01:12:55.945 --> 01:12:58.820
And I hope it's another
highlight of this course

01:12:58.820 --> 01:13:01.650
to describe light forces in
the dressed atom picture.

01:13:01.650 --> 01:13:03.840
But what I want to
do here is already

01:13:03.840 --> 01:13:05.480
in preparation for that.

01:13:05.480 --> 01:13:10.080
I want to not yet
introduce forces, simply

01:13:10.080 --> 01:13:14.690
figure out what happens in
the dressed atom picture

01:13:14.690 --> 01:13:16.590
when the atoms scatter light.

01:13:16.590 --> 01:13:18.520
And you know already
the solution.

01:13:18.520 --> 01:13:21.740
The solution is
the Mollow triplet.

01:13:21.740 --> 01:13:25.710
And we have discussed with
the Optical Bloch Equations

01:13:25.710 --> 01:13:28.260
that at low laser power,
the Mollow triplet

01:13:28.260 --> 01:13:34.160
has three curves.

01:13:34.160 --> 01:13:36.930
It has three broadened curves.

01:13:36.930 --> 01:13:39.010
And they have
different broadening.

01:13:39.010 --> 01:13:41.860
And I didn't prove it to
you, but I mentioned to you,

01:13:41.860 --> 01:13:47.112
at low laser power there is--
perturbative laser power,

01:13:47.112 --> 01:13:49.570
we discussed at great length
that there's a delta function.

01:13:49.570 --> 01:13:52.870
And at low laser power,
the delta function remains.

01:13:52.870 --> 01:13:55.720
So this is sort of the
spectrum we get out of it.

01:13:55.720 --> 01:13:57.670
And what I want
to show you now is

01:13:57.670 --> 01:14:04.350
how this spectrum is described
in the dressed atom picture.

01:14:04.350 --> 01:14:07.210
Atom photon interaction
has a wonderful discussion

01:14:07.210 --> 01:14:08.580
of all the details.

01:14:08.580 --> 01:14:11.260
I will share with
you a few highlights.

01:14:11.260 --> 01:14:14.990
But we will go much further in
the description of the Mollow

01:14:14.990 --> 01:14:17.760
triplet then we've gone before.

01:14:17.760 --> 01:14:22.460
But I will not go into
all excruciating details.

01:14:22.460 --> 01:14:27.310
So let's discuss first.

01:14:27.310 --> 01:14:29.100
That's something we
hadn't done so far.

01:14:29.100 --> 01:14:32.050
What are the intensities
in this Mollow triplet?

01:14:35.340 --> 01:14:45.430
So the way how we obtain
it is the following.

01:14:45.430 --> 01:14:51.080
We have the manifold, the
manifold with N minus 1

01:14:51.080 --> 01:14:53.200
and the manifold with N photons.

01:14:53.200 --> 01:14:56.140
And this is the detuning.

01:14:56.140 --> 01:14:59.160
And if we allow for the
atom laser coupling,

01:14:59.160 --> 01:15:02.520
the splitting here is a
generalized Rabi frequency.

01:15:02.520 --> 01:15:06.160
And well, you immediately see
that in this picture, if you

01:15:06.160 --> 01:15:09.250
allow spontaneous emission from
the upper manifold to the lower

01:15:09.250 --> 01:15:13.620
manifold, you have four
different combinations.

01:15:13.620 --> 01:15:16.520
One is the long photon
is the blue sideband.

01:15:16.520 --> 01:15:18.367
This is the red sideband.

01:15:18.367 --> 01:15:19.450
This is the blue sideband.

01:15:19.450 --> 01:15:20.500
This is the red sideband.

01:15:20.500 --> 01:15:23.210
And those two are the carriers.

01:15:23.210 --> 01:15:25.480
But now, we can
do the following.

01:15:25.480 --> 01:15:28.610
I've just written down for
you the solution of the wave

01:15:28.610 --> 01:15:30.530
function with sine
and cosine theta.

01:15:37.300 --> 01:15:41.950
If we want to emit the blue
sideband, we go from the top

01:15:41.950 --> 01:15:43.930
to the bottom.

01:15:43.930 --> 01:15:47.320
But that means, since a
photon in the rotating wave

01:15:47.320 --> 01:15:53.980
approximation can only be
emitted when we go from b to a,

01:15:53.980 --> 01:15:57.890
we find that the
matrix element for that

01:15:57.890 --> 01:16:02.240
involves cosine theta
times sine theta.

01:16:02.240 --> 01:16:04.480
However, if you want
to emit the carrier,

01:16:04.480 --> 01:16:07.300
you go from here to there.

01:16:07.300 --> 01:16:11.970
Well, we always have to find
the excited state to begin with.

01:16:11.970 --> 01:16:21.000
And we go-- I must
have made a mistake.

01:16:24.340 --> 01:16:24.850
Sorry.

01:16:24.850 --> 01:16:26.660
When I went to emit
the blue side, when

01:16:26.660 --> 01:16:28.880
I go from all the way
up to all the way down,

01:16:28.880 --> 01:16:31.650
and I always have to find
an excited state which

01:16:31.650 --> 01:16:33.070
connects to the ground state.

01:16:33.070 --> 01:16:37.865
And this gives me a term,
which is cosine square.

01:16:37.865 --> 01:16:41.290
The red detuned sideband
gives me sine squared.

01:16:41.290 --> 01:16:46.600
And if I want to get
the carrier, this one,

01:16:46.600 --> 01:16:48.410
I go from here to here.

01:16:48.410 --> 01:16:51.090
I get cosine theta sine theta.

01:16:51.090 --> 01:16:53.570
So in other words,
we can immediately

01:16:53.570 --> 01:16:56.640
read off the matrix elements.

01:16:56.640 --> 01:16:59.240
And since the intensity,
Fermi's Golden Rule,

01:16:59.240 --> 01:17:01.290
is the matrix
element squared, we

01:17:01.290 --> 01:17:05.410
find immediately that the upper
lower sideband and the carrier

01:17:05.410 --> 01:17:09.340
involve terms cosine to the
4 theta, sine to the 4 theta,

01:17:09.340 --> 01:17:11.510
cosine square sine square.

01:17:11.510 --> 01:17:13.670
So we got the matrix element.

01:17:13.670 --> 01:17:15.560
And the only thing
we have to know now

01:17:15.560 --> 01:17:22.530
is that the width or the rate
is given by the matrix element.

01:17:27.370 --> 01:17:30.290
The rate is given by the
matrix element square.

01:17:30.290 --> 01:17:34.330
But now, what is the
intensity of the line?

01:17:34.330 --> 01:17:38.720
Well, the upper
sideband is emitted

01:17:38.720 --> 01:17:40.580
by the upper dressed
state, because you

01:17:40.580 --> 01:17:42.270
have to go from the
upper dressed state

01:17:42.270 --> 01:17:45.430
to the lower dressed state to
get the blue detuned photon.

01:17:45.430 --> 01:17:48.050
So therefore, the
intensity for this sideband

01:17:48.050 --> 01:17:51.380
is this rate times
the population

01:17:51.380 --> 01:17:54.260
in the upper dressed state.

01:17:54.260 --> 01:17:56.560
So what is missing
at this point,

01:17:56.560 --> 01:18:00.100
and we need that urgently
for next week, what

01:18:00.100 --> 01:18:04.740
is the population in the
upper and the lower sideband?

01:18:04.740 --> 01:18:08.320
Well, we know the
transition rates

01:18:08.320 --> 01:18:10.510
between the upper and
the lower sidebands--

01:18:10.510 --> 01:18:13.840
well, between the upper
and lower dressed state.

01:18:13.840 --> 01:18:18.572
We know we've just
found here the rate.

01:18:18.572 --> 01:18:19.280
What is the rate?

01:18:19.280 --> 01:18:23.970
What is the matrix element
squared when you go from one

01:18:23.970 --> 01:18:27.820
is the upper, two is the
lower state of the manifold.

01:18:27.820 --> 01:18:30.140
So we have just
gotten those rates.

01:18:30.140 --> 01:18:34.110
And rate equation says,
the change of population

01:18:34.110 --> 01:18:38.370
in the upper dressed
state is given

01:18:38.370 --> 01:18:41.040
by the departure
from the upper state

01:18:41.040 --> 01:18:44.970
and what arrives
from the lower state.

01:18:44.970 --> 01:18:49.110
So since we are interested
in the steady state solution,

01:18:49.110 --> 01:18:52.940
we can just set the
left side to zero.

01:18:52.940 --> 01:18:56.190
And then, the rate
equations simply

01:18:56.190 --> 01:19:00.250
give us the population
in terms of the rates.

01:19:00.250 --> 01:19:03.750
So in other words, if you
ask, what is the steady state

01:19:03.750 --> 01:19:06.370
solution in the upper
or lower dressed state,

01:19:06.370 --> 01:19:10.510
it's given by a ratio of
those rate coefficients.

01:19:10.510 --> 01:19:12.450
But we just got those
rate coefficients.

01:19:12.450 --> 01:19:18.030
And this gives us another bunch
of sine and cosine functions.

01:19:18.030 --> 01:19:20.350
So in other words,
we know now what

01:19:20.350 --> 01:19:23.450
is the population of
the dressed states.

01:19:23.450 --> 01:19:26.700
I mean, everything is expressed
by one non-trivial parameter

01:19:26.700 --> 01:19:27.520
theta.

01:19:27.520 --> 01:19:31.260
And all we get is sine square,
cosine square, sine to the 4th,

01:19:31.260 --> 01:19:33.110
we just get those
trigonometric functions.

01:19:38.180 --> 01:19:38.720
Yes.

01:19:38.720 --> 01:19:42.230
I think we can finish that.

01:19:42.230 --> 01:19:42.730
Good.

01:19:48.240 --> 01:19:50.550
